TY  - JOUR
AU  - Di Maggio, Marco
AU  - Pagano, Marco
T1  - Financial Disclosure and Market Transparency with Costly Information Processing*
PY  - 2018
Y1  - 2018/02/01
DO  - 10.1093/rof/rfx009
JO  - Review of Finance
JA  - Rev Financ
VL  - 22
IS  - 1
SP  - 117
EP  - 153
SN  - 1572-3097
AB  - We study a model where some investors (“hedgers”) are bad at information processing, while others (“speculators”) have superior information-processing ability and trade purely to exploit it. The disclosure of financial information induces a trade externality: if speculators refrain from trading, hedgers do the same, depressing the asset price. Market transparency reinforces this mechanism, by making speculators’ trades more visible to hedgers. Hence, issuers will oppose both the disclosure of fundamentals and trading transparency. Issuers may either under- or over-provide information compared to the socially efficient level if speculators have more bargaining power than hedgers, while they never under-provide it otherwise. When hedgers have low financial literacy, forbidding their access to the market may be socially efficient.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rof/rfx009
ER  - 



